\section{Multivariate Problems}
%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Multivariate Problems}
A function of several variables is, as the name indicates, a function that takes in several variables and outputs a value associated to the inputs.
\begin{itemize}
    \item{The function $f(x, y) = x + y$ takes in two values $x$ and $y$ and outputs their sum $x + y$}
    \item{The function $g(x, y, z) = xyz^2$ takes in three values $x$, $y$, and $z$, and outputs the product $xyz^2$.}
\end{itemize}
\\~\\
Domain and Range of a Function
\begin{itemize}
    \item{In univariate optimization, a function of several variables has a domain and a range: the domain is the set of input values and the range is the set of output values.}
    \item{For a function of two variables $f(x, y)$, the domain is now a subset of the 2-dimensional plane rather than a subset of the real line. Because of this, domains of functions of more than one variable can be rather complicated.}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
