\section{Partial Derivatives}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Partial Derivatives}
Partial derivatives are simply the usual notion of differentiation applied to functions of more than one variable.
However, since we now have more than one variable, we also have more than one natural way to compute a derivative.
\begin{tcolorbox}[colback = blue!5, colframe = blue!40!black, title = Critical Point]
For a function $f(x, y)$ of two variables, we define the partial derivative of $f$ with respect to $x$ as
$$ \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{f(x+h, y) - f(x, y)}{h} $$
and the partial derivative of $f$ with respect to $y$ as 
$$ \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{f(x, y + h) - f(x, y)}{h} $$
\end{tcolorbox}
\end{frame}
%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Partial Derivatives}
To evaluate a partial derivative of the function $f$ with respect to $x$, we need only pretend that all the other variables (i.e., everything except $x$) that $f$ depends on are constants, and then just evaluate the derivative of $f$ with respect to $x$ as a normal one-variable derivative.
\\~\\
\textbf{Example 1}
\begin{itemize}
    \item{Find $f_x$ and $f_y$ for $f(x, y) = x^3y^2 + e^x$.}
    \item{For $f_x$, we treat $y$ as a constant and $x$ as the variable. Thus, we see that
            $$ f_x = 3x^2 y^2 + e^x $$}
    \item{Similarly, to find $f_y$, we instead treat $x$ as a constant and $y$ as the variable, to get
            $$ f_y = x^3 \cdot 2y + 0 = 2x^3y $$}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Partial Derivatives}
To evaluate a partial derivative of the function $f$ with respect to $x$, we need only pretend that all the other variables (i.e., everything except $x$) that $f$ depends on are constants, and then just evaluate the derivative of $f$ with respect to $x$ as a normal one-variable derivative.
\\~\\
\textbf{Example 2}
\begin{itemize}
    \item{Find $f_x$ and $f_y$ for $\ln{(x^2 + y^2)}$.}
    \item{For $f_x$, we treat $y$ as a constant and $x$ as the variable. Thus, we see that
            $$ f_x = \frac{2x}{x^2 + y^2} $$}
    \item{Similarly, to find $f_y$, we instead treat $x$ as a constant and $y$ as the variable, to get
            $$ f_y = \frac{2y}{x^2 + y^2} $$}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
