\section{Classifying Critical Points}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Classifying Critical Points}
Now that we have a list of critical points (namely, the places that a function could potentially have a minimum or maximum value) we would like to know whether those points actually are minima or maxima of $f$.

\begin{tcolorbox}[colback = blue!5, colframe = blue!40!black, title = Critical Point]
The discriminant (also called the Hessian) at a critical point is the value $$ D = f_{xx} \cdot f_{yy} - (f_{xy})^2 $$
where each of the second-order partials is evaluated at the critical point.
\end{tcolorbox}
One way to remember the definition of the discriminant is as the determinant of the matrix of the four second-order partials:
$$ D =  \begin{vmatrix}
            f_{xx} & f_{xy} \\
            f_{yx} & f_{yy}
        \end{vmatrix}
$$
\textbf{Example:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item{For $g(x, y) = x^2 + y^2$ we have $g_{xx} = g_{yy} = 2$ and $g_{xy} = 0$ so $D = 4$ at the origin.}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Classifying Critical Points}

\begin{tcolorbox}[colback = blue!5, colframe = blue!40!black, title = Critical Point]
Suppose $P$ is a critical point of $f(x, y)$, and let $D$ be the value of the discriminant $f_{xx}f_{yy} - f^2_{xy}$ at $P$. If $D > 0$ and $f_{xx} > 0$, then the critical point is a minimum. If $D > 0$ and $f_{xx} < 0$, then the critical point is a maximum. If $D < 0$, then the critical point is a saddle point. (If $D = 0$, then the test is inconclusive.)
\end{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Proof: } \\
Assume for simplicity that $P$ is at the origin. Then one may show that the function $f(x, y) − f(P)$ is closely approximated by the polynomial $ax^2 + bxy + cy^2$, where $a =\frac{1}{2}f_{xx}$, $b = f_{xy}$,and $c = \frac{1}{2}f_{yy}$. 
\\~\\
If $D \neq 0$, then the behavior of $f(x, y)$ near the critical point $P$ will be the same as that quadratic polynomial. Completing the square and examining whether the resulting quadratic polynomial has any real roots and whether it opens or downwards yields the test.
\end{frame}
%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Classifying Critical Points}
We can combine the above results to yield a procedure for finding and classifying the critical points of a function $f(x, y)$:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item{Compute both partial derivatives $f_y$ and $f_y$.}
    \item{Find all points $(x, y)$ where both partial derivatives are zero, or where (at least) one of the partial derivatives is undefined.}
    \item{At each critical point, evaluate $D = f_{xx} \cdot f_{yy} - (f_{xy})^2$ and apply the \textbf{Second Derivatives Test}:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item{If $D > 0$ and $f_{xx} > 0 \longrightarrow$ local minimum}
        \item{If $D > 0$ and $f_{xx} < 0 \longrightarrow$ local maximum}
        \item{If $D < 0 \longrightarrow$ saddle point}
    \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}
\end{frame}
%------------------------------------------------
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Classifying Critical Points}
\textbf{Example: Verify that $f(x, y) = x^2 + y^2$ has only one critical point, a minimum at the origin.}
\begin{itemize}
    \item{First, we have $f_x = 2x$ and $f_y = 2y$. Since they are both defined everywhere, we need only find where they are both zero.}
    \item{Setting both partial derivatives equal to zero yields $x = 0$ and $y = 0$, so the only critical point is $(0, 0)$.}
    \item{To classify the critical points, we compute $f_{xx} = 2$, $f_{xy} = 0$, and $f_{yy} = 2$. Then $D = 2 \cdot 2 − 0^2 = 4$}
    \item{So, by the classification test, since $D > 0$ and $f_{xx} > 0$ at $(0, 0)$, we see that $(0, 0)$ is a \textbf{local minimum}.}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
